<p>Presumably the eye is Bleistein's - however, in the
        previous stanza Bleistein's features were described in
        the plural, and 'eyes' would be expected here. Hence it
        is often thought that this eye does not refer to
        Bleistein, but someone else. But single eye may refer to
        Whitman's 'protrusive lip' (see protrusive).</p>
